VALUES
(20, 20, 13, 13, 'kjv', 'Love not sleep, lest thou come to poverty;', 0, 42, 'connection', 'Work Ethic in Proverbs', 'This phrase echoes the theme found in Proverbs 6:9-11, where the sluggard is admonished to consider the ant and learn diligence. Both passages highlight the dangers of laziness and the consequences of neglecting responsibility, reinforcing the idea that a strong work ethic is essential for prosperity.', 'link', '[{"type": "crossReference", "reference": "Proverbs 6:9-11", "description": "Admonition against slothfulness"}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(20, 20, 13, 13, 'kjv', 'open thine eyes, and thou shalt be satisfied with bread.', 43, 99, 'theology', 'Spiritual Awareness and Provision', 'This directive to ''open thine eyes'' suggests a deeper spiritual awareness necessary to recognize God''s provision. Many scholars believe this reflects the biblical principle that spiritual insight often leads to material blessing, aligning with Matthew 6:33, which encourages seeking God''s kingdom first for all necessities.', 'sparkles', '[{"type": "crossReference", "reference": "Matthew 6:33", "description": "Seek first the Kingdom of God"}]'::jsonb, 'standard', true, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(20, 20, 13, 13, 'kjv', 'Love not sleep, lest thou come to poverty;', 0, 42, 'question', 'Implications of Laziness', 'What practical steps can you take to avoid the ''sleep'' of complacency in your life? How might this verse challenge you to stay alert in both your spiritual walk and daily responsibilities?', 'questionmark.circle.fill', NULL, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(20, 20, 13, 13, 'kjv', 'open thine eyes, and thou shalt be satisfied with bread.', 43, 99, 'greek', 'Understanding ''Eyes''', 'עיניים (ayin, H5869) - eyes, sight, understanding. This Hebrew term emphasizes the importance of perception and insight, suggesting that spiritual and practical awareness can lead to fulfillment and sustenance.', 'textformat.abc', '[{"type": "strongs", "reference": "H5869", "description": "Strong''s definition of ''eyes''"}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(20, 20, 14, 14, 'kjv', 'It is naught, it is naught, saith the buyer:', 0, 44, 'connection', 'Buyer Deception', 'This phrase echoes the warning found in Proverbs 11:1, ''A false balance is an abomination to the Lord, but a just weight is His delight.'' Both verses highlight the theme of dishonesty in commerce. The connection emphasizes the moral imperative for integrity in business dealings, illustrating how deceptive practices can lead to greater consequences.', 'link', '[{"type": "crossReference", "reference": "Proverbs 11:1", "description": "A verse emphasizing the importance of honesty in transactions."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(20, 20, 14, 14, 'kjv', 'but when he is gone his way, then he boasteth.', 45, 91, 'theology', 'Pride in Acquisition', 'This passage suggests that human nature often leads to pride following a successful negotiation, even if initial claims were deceptive. Many scholars believe this reflects the broader biblical principle of humility versus pride, as seen in James 4:6, ''God resists the proud, but gives grace to the humble.'' The contrast reminds believers to cultivate humility in their dealings.', 'sparkles', '[{"type": "crossReference", "reference": "James 4:6", "description": "A verse that contrasts pride with humility."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', true, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(20, 20, 14, 14, 'kjv', 'It is naught, it is naught, saith the buyer:', 0, 44, 'question', 'Value Perception', 'What does the buyer''s claim of ''naught'' reveal about the nature of value and perception in our lives? How often do we undervalue what is truly precious, both materially and spiritually, for the sake of immediate gain or appearance?', 'questionmark.circle.fill', NULL, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(20, 20, 14, 14, 'kjv', 'then he boasteth.', 74, 91, 'greek', 'Boasting in Acquisition', 'καυχάομαι (kaucháomai, G2744) - to boast, to glory. This term conveys the idea of taking pride in one''s possessions or achievements. In the context of Proverbs 20:14, it highlights the futility of boasting over ill-gotten gains, drawing attention to the moral implications of pride in deceitful transactions.', 'textformat.abc', '[{"type": "strongs", "reference": "G2744", "description": "Strong''s number for the Greek word ''kauch\u00e1omai''."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(20, 20, 15, 15, 'kjv', 'There is gold, and a multitude of rubies: but the lips of knowledge are a precious jewel.', 0, 89, 'connection', 'Value of Wisdom', 'Proverbs 3:13-15 states, ''Happy is the man that findeth wisdom, and the man that getteth understanding. For the merchandise of it is better than the merchandise of silver, and the gain thereof than fine gold.'' This connection emphasizes that while material wealth is valuable, the pursuit of wisdom and knowledge is far more rewarding and fulfilling.', 'link', '[{"type": "crossReference", "reference": "Proverbs 3:13-15", "description": "Emphasizes the superiority of wisdom over material wealth."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(20, 20, 15, 15, 'kjv', 'the lips of knowledge', 46, 67, 'greek', 'Knowledge in Scripture', 'ἡ γνώσις (hē gnōsis, G1108) - knowledge, insight, wisdom. This term often conveys a deeper spiritual understanding that surpasses mere factual knowledge, aligning with the biblical theme that true wisdom comes from God.', 'textformat.abc', '[{"type": "strongs", "reference": "G1108", "description": "Greek term for knowledge, emphasizing spiritual insight."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(20, 20, 15, 15, 'kjv', 'a precious jewel', 72, 88, 'theology', 'Treasures of Wisdom', 'Many scholars believe that this phrase reflects the biblical doctrine that wisdom and knowledge are to be treasured above all earthly possessions. This concept aligns with Matthew 13:44, where the kingdom of heaven is likened to a treasure hidden in a field, illustrating the incomparable value of spiritual riches.', 'sparkles', '[{"type": "crossReference", "reference": "Matthew 13:44", "description": "Illustrates the value of spiritual treasures compared to worldly riches."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', true, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(20, 20, 15, 15, 'kjv', 'a multitude of rubies', 19, 40, 'question', 'What Do We Value?', 'How does the comparison between material wealth and knowledge challenge your personal values and priorities? In what ways can you seek knowledge that surpasses the allure of tangible riches?', 'questionmark.circle.fill', NULL, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(20, 20, 16, 16, 'kjv', 'Take his garment that is surety for a stranger', 0, 46, 'connection', 'Surety and Responsibility', 'This phrase connects to Proverbs 22:26-27, which warns against being surety for a stranger. The theme emphasizes the importance of wisdom in financial dealings and the potential risks involved. Engaging in suretyship without careful consideration can lead to loss and hardship, highlighting the need for discernment in our commitments.', 'link', '[{"type": "crossReference", "reference": "Proverbs 22:26-27", "description": "Warns against being surety for others."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(20, 20, 16, 16, 'kjv', 'and take a pledge of him for a strange woman', 48, 92, 'theology', 'Cautions Against Deceit', 'This passage suggests a theological caution against engaging with ''strange women,'' often interpreted as a metaphor for temptation and moral compromise. Many scholars believe that this reflects the broader biblical principle of avoiding relationships that could lead one away from faithfulness to God, emphasizing the importance of integrity in all areas of life.', 'sparkles', NULL, 'standard', true, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(20, 20, 16, 16, 'kjv', 'Take his garment that is surety for a stranger', 0, 46, 'question', 'Understanding Financial Commitments', 'What does this directive about taking a garment as surety reveal about the nature of trust and responsibility in our relationships? How can we apply this wisdom in today''s financial interactions and commitments?', 'questionmark.circle.fill', NULL, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(20, 20, 17, 17, 'kjv', 'Bread of deceit is sweet to a man;', 0, 34, 'connection', 'Deceit and Temptation', 'This phrase resonates with James 1:14-15, which notes that temptation can appear enticing but ultimately leads to sin and death. Recognizing the sweetness of deceit helps believers understand the deceptive nature of sin, encouraging vigilance against temptation.', 'link', '[{"type": "crossReference", "reference": "James 1:14-15", "description": "Illustrates how temptation leads to sin, paralleling the deceptive sweetness referenced in Proverbs."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(20, 20, 17, 17, 'kjv', 'but afterwards his mouth shall be filled with gravel.', 35, 88, 'theology', 'Consequences of Sin', 'Many scholars believe this imagery illustrates the bitter consequences of engaging in deceitful practices. The metaphor of ''gravel'' signifies emptiness and discomfort, underscoring the theological principle that sin leads to suffering and disillusionment.', 'sparkles', NULL, 'standard', true, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(20, 20, 17, 17, 'kjv', 'Bread of deceit is sweet to a man;', 0, 34, 'question', 'Nature of Deceit', 'What lessons can we learn from the allure of deceit as described in this verse, and how can we guard against its temptations in our daily lives?', 'questionmark.circle.fill', NULL, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(20, 20, 17, 17, 'kjv', 'but afterwards his mouth shall be filled with gravel.', 35, 88, 'greek', 'Gravel Significance', 'גָּרוּב (garub, H1643) - gravel, dust. This term emphasizes the harsh reality of deceitful actions, indicating that what seems appealing can lead to a desolate and uncomfortable reality.', 'textformat.abc', '[{"type": "strongs", "reference": "H1643", "description": "The Strong''s number for gravel, highlighting its implications in the context."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(20, 20, 18, 18, 'kjv', 'Every purpose is established by counsel: ', 0, 41, 'connection', 'Purpose in Counsel', 'This phrase echoes Proverbs 15:22, which states, ''Without counsel plans fail, but with many advisers they succeed.'' The connection highlights the importance of seeking wisdom and guidance in decision-making. It reinforces the idea that collaboration and counsel are crucial for establishing sound purposes in life.', 'link', '[{"type": "crossReference", "reference": "Proverbs 15:22", "description": "Highlights the importance of counsel in achieving success."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(20, 20, 18, 18, 'kjv', 'and with good advice make war.', 41, 71, 'theology', 'Wisdom in Warfare', 'This passage suggests that engaging in conflict should not be taken lightly; rather, it emphasizes the necessity of sound advice. Many scholars believe this reflects the broader theological principle that God''s people should approach challenges and conflicts with thoughtful preparation and divine guidance, as seen in Ephesians 6:10-18 where believers are instructed to put on the armor of God.', 'sparkles', '[{"type": "crossReference", "reference": "Ephesians 6:10-18", "description": "Discusses spiritual preparation for conflict."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', true, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(20, 20, 18, 18, 'kjv', 'Every purpose is established by counsel: ', 0, 41, 'question', 'Purpose and Counsel Reflection', 'What steps can you take to seek wise counsel in your current decisions? How might involving others in your plans change the outcome?', 'lightbulb', NULL, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(20, 20, 18, 18, 'kjv', 'with good advice make war.', 45, 71, 'greek', 'Advice and Strategy', 'συμβουλή (sumboulē, G4823) - counsel, advice. This term indicates not just any advice, but a strategic and wise counsel that should guide significant actions, especially in matters of conflict, highlighting the necessity of discernment.', 'textformat.abc', '[{"type": "strongs", "reference": "G4823", "description": "Strong''s number for the Greek term for counsel."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(20, 20, 19, 19, 'kjv', 'He that goeth about as a talebearer revealeth secrets', 0, 53, 'connection', 'Proverbs on Gossip', 'This phrase parallels Proverbs 11:13, which states, ''A talebearer revealeth secrets: but he that is of a faithful spirit concealeth the matter.'' This connection underscores the destructive nature of gossip and the importance of discretion. Both verses emphasize the need for integrity in communication.', 'link', '[{"type": "crossReference", "reference": "Proverbs 11:13", "description": "Demonstrates the contrast between a talebearer and a faithful person."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(20, 20, 19, 19, 'kjv', 'therefore meddle not with him that flattereth with his lips.', 55, 115, 'question', 'Flattery''s Impact', 'What does it mean to ''meddle not'' with those who flatter? In what ways can flattery distract us from truth and genuine relationships? Reflecting on this can help us discern the motivations behind the words of others and encourage us to seek authenticity in our interactions.', 'lightbulb', NULL, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(20, 20, 19, 19, 'kjv', 'He that goeth about as a talebearer revealeth secrets', 0, 53, 'theology', 'Nature of Sin', 'This passage highlights the theological concept of sin as relational harm. Many scholars believe that revealing secrets damages community and trust, which are central to God''s design for human relationships. This underscores the importance of guarding our tongues as part of living a life reflective of God''s love.', 'sparkles', '[{"type": "commentary", "reference": "Matthew Henry''s Commentary", "description": "Discusses the relational consequences of gossip and the call to integrity."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', true, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(20, 20, 19, 19, 'kjv', 'therefore meddle not with him that flattereth with his lips.', 55, 115, 'greek', 'Understanding Flattery', 'χαριεντίζω (charientizō, G5485) - to be charming, or to flatter. This term indicates a superficiality in communication, often leading to manipulation. Understanding this term enriches our comprehension of the dangers of flattery, as it relates to a deeper moral teaching found throughout Proverbs.', 'textformat.abc', '[{"type": "strongs", "reference": "G5485", "description": "Strong''s number for the Greek term related to flattery."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(20, 20, 20, 20, 'kjv', 'Whoso curseth his father or his mother,', 0, 39, 'connection', 'Parental Honor in Scripture', 'This phrase echoes the commandment found in Exodus 20:12, ''Honor your father and your mother.'' The severity of cursing one''s parents emphasizes the weight of this commandment. Both verses highlight the foundational role of family respect in maintaining societal order and divine favor. Disrespect towards parents not only goes against God''s law but also invites serious consequences.', 'link', '[{"type": "crossReference", "reference": "Exodus 20:12", "description": "A foundational commandment emphasizing the importance of honoring parents."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(20, 20, 20, 20, 'kjv', 'his lamp shall be put out', 40, 65, 'theology', 'Symbolism of the Lamp', 'Many scholars believe that the ''lamp'' symbolizes life, guidance, and God''s favor. In biblical literature, a lamp often represents one''s spiritual state and relationship with God. The extinguishing of one''s lamp suggests a dire consequence of severing ties with divine wisdom and familial respect. Such imagery reminds believers of the importance of maintaining a righteous path.', 'sparkles', NULL, 'standard', true, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(20, 20, 20, 20, 'kjv', 'in obscure darkness.', 66, 86, 'question', 'Understanding ''Obscure Darkness''', 'What does ''obscure darkness'' signify in the context of spiritual consequences? Does it reflect a state of separation from God or an absence of clarity in one''s life? Reflecting on this phrase can lead to deeper understanding of the spiritual ramifications of our actions, especially regarding familial relationships.', 'questionmark.circle.fill', NULL, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(20, 20, 21, 21, 'kjv', 'An inheritance may be gotten hastily at the beginning;', 0, 54, 'connection', 'Caution Against Hasty Wealth', 'This phrase resonates with Proverbs 13:11, which states, ''Wealth gained hastily will dwindle, but whoever gathers little by little will increase it.'' Both verses warn against the dangers of seeking quick wealth, emphasizing that true prosperity comes from patience and diligence. This connection highlights the biblical principle that enduring success is built over time rather than through sudden gain.', 'link', '[{"type": "crossReference", "reference": "Proverbs 13:11", "description": "Similar warning about hasty wealth"}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(20, 20, 21, 21, 'kjv', 'but the end thereof shall not be blessed.', 55, 96, 'theology', 'The Principle of Endings', 'Many scholars believe this verse reflects a broader theological principle that God values the outcomes of our choices. The ''end'' of an endeavor is often more significant than its beginning, suggesting that God desires blessings that endure. This aligns with Romans 8:28, which assures believers that all things work together for good for those who love God, emphasizing a divine oversight in the journey toward fulfillment.', 'sparkles', '[{"type": "crossReference", "reference": "Romans 8:28", "description": "Affirms God''s purpose in outcomes"}]'::jsonb, 'standard', true, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(20, 20, 21, 21, 'kjv', 'An inheritance may be gotten hastily at the beginning;', 0, 54, 'question', 'Reflection on Inheritance', 'What does it mean to receive an inheritance quickly, and how might this affect one''s character and faith? Consider the potential spiritual implications of gaining wealth without effort. Does this align with the biblical call to stewardship and responsibility?', 'lightbulb', NULL, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(20, 20, 22, 22, 'kjv', 'Say not thou, I will recompense evil;', 0, 37, 'connection', 'Biblical Response to Evil', 'This phrase connects with Romans 12:19, where Paul instructs believers not to take revenge but to leave room for God''s wrath. Both verses highlight the importance of trusting God to handle injustices, reinforcing the theme of divine justice over personal retribution. This underscores a consistent biblical principle that encourages patience and reliance on God''s timing.', 'link', '[{"type": "crossReference", "reference": "Romans 12:19", "description": "Paul''s teaching on vengeance"}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(20, 20, 22, 22, 'kjv', 'but wait on the Lord,', 38, 59, 'theology', 'The Value of Patience', 'Many scholars believe that ''waiting on the Lord'' signifies an active trust and expectation for God''s intervention in difficult circumstances. This reflects the theological concept of hope, which is foundational in Christian doctrine, suggesting that patience is not passive but an expression of faith in God''s sovereignty and timing.', 'sparkles', '[{"type": "commentary", "reference": "Matthew Henry''s Commentary", "description": "Insight on patience and trust"}]'::jsonb, 'standard', true, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(20, 20, 22, 22, 'kjv', 'and he shall save thee.', 60, 83, 'greek', 'Salvation in Context', 'σωτήριον (sōtērion, G4991) - salvation, deliverance, rescue. This term indicates not only spiritual salvation but also deliverance in practical life situations. Understanding this word in the context of the verse emphasizes that waiting on the Lord includes expecting His help in both spiritual and earthly matters.', 'textformat.abc', '[{"type": "strongs", "reference": "G4991", "description": "Strong''s Greek Lexicon entry"}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(20, 20, 22, 22, 'kjv', 'Say not thou, I will recompense evil;', 0, 37, 'question', 'Reflecting on Vengeance', 'What does it reveal about our character when we feel the urge to take vengeance? How can this verse reshape our understanding of justice and mercy in our daily interactions?', 'questionmark.circle.fill', NULL, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(20, 20, 23, 23, 'kjv', 'Divers weights are an abomination unto the Lord;', 0, 48, 'connection', 'Abomination in Scripture', 'The term ''abomination'' appears frequently in Scripture, indicating something detestable to God. For example, Deuteronomy 25:13-16 addresses dishonest weights, underscoring God''s disdain for unfair practices. This connection highlights the seriousness of integrity in transactions, as dishonesty not only harms others but also incurs divine displeasure.', 'link', '[{"type": "crossReference", "reference": "Deuteronomy 25:13-16", "description": "Addresses the use of dishonest weights and God''s commandments."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(20, 20, 23, 23, 'kjv', 'and a false balance is not good.', 49, 81, 'theology', 'The Importance of Justice', 'This verse reflects the biblical principle that God values justice and fairness. Many scholars believe that this principle extends beyond commerce into all areas of life, emphasizing that believers are called to uphold truth and integrity in their dealings. This foundational concept is essential for fostering a just society in accordance with God''s character.', 'sparkles', NULL, 'standard', true, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(20, 20, 23, 23, 'kjv', 'Divers weights are an abomination unto the Lord;', 0, 48, 'greek', 'Understanding ''Abomination''', 'עַבְרָה (toʿebah, H8441) - abomination, something that is detestable or repugnant. This term reflects God''s strong aversion to practices that violate His standards of righteousness, showing that integrity is paramount in relationships and commerce.', 'character.book.closed', '[{"type": "strongs", "reference": "H8441", "description": "Refers to the Hebrew word for abomination."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(20, 20, 23, 23, 'kjv', 'Divers weights are an abomination unto the Lord;', 0, 48, 'question', 'Reflecting on Integrity', 'What specific practices in my life may reflect a ''false balance'' that God finds displeasing? How can I ensure that my actions align with the integrity that pleases Him?', 'questionmark.circle.fill', NULL, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(20, 20, 24, 24, 'kjv', 'Man’s goings are of the Lord;', 0, 29, 'connection', 'Divine Sovereignty', 'This phrase connects to Proverbs 16:9, which states, ''A man''s heart deviseth his way: but the Lord directeth his steps.'' Both verses emphasize the belief that while humans make plans and choices, ultimately it is God who guides their paths. This highlights the sovereignty of God in human affairs and invites reflection on the importance of seeking divine guidance in our decisions.', 'link', '[{"type": "crossReference", "reference": "Proverbs 16:9", "description": "Emphasizes God''s control over human plans."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(20, 20, 24, 24, 'kjv', 'how can a man then understand his own way?', 30, 72, 'theology', 'Understanding and Divine Will', 'Many scholars believe this verse reflects a key theological principle: the limitations of human understanding in light of God’s omniscience. It suggests that humans, in their finite state, cannot fully grasp their life paths without divine insight. This notion is prevalent in Christian theology, which asserts that reliance on God''s wisdom leads to true understanding.', 'sparkles', '[{"type": "commentary", "reference": "Matthew Henry''s Commentary", "description": "Discusses the limitations of human understanding."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', true, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(20, 20, 24, 24, 'kjv', 'Man’s goings are of the Lord;', 0, 29, 'greek', 'Key Term Analysis', 'The Hebrew word for ''goings'' is מַהֲלָכוֹת (mahalakhot, H1980) - ways, paths. This term underscores the various directions and choices in life. The use of ''Lord'' indicates a personal God involved in directing these paths, reinforcing the belief in divine guidance throughout one''s journey.', 'textformat.abc', '[{"type": "strongs", "reference": "H1980", "description": "Refers to the Hebrew word for ways or paths."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(20, 20, 24, 24, 'kjv', 'how can a man then understand his own way?', 30, 72, 'question', 'Reflection on Understanding', 'In what ways do you seek to discern God’s direction in your life? Considering the notion that our paths are directed by the Lord, how can we cultivate a deeper reliance on Him for understanding our decisions and life’s journey?', 'lightbulb', NULL, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(20, 20, 25, 25, 'kjv', 'It is a snare to the man who devoureth that which is holy,', 0, 58, 'connection', 'Cross-Reference to Leviticus', 'This phrase connects to Leviticus 22:10-16, where the Israelites are warned against profaning holy offerings. Both passages highlight the gravity of treating sacred things lightly and the consequences that follow. Understanding this link emphasizes the seriousness with which God views holiness and the reverence required in approaching what is set apart for Him.', 'link', '[{"type": "crossReference", "reference": "Leviticus 22:10-16", "description": "Warnings against profaning holy offerings"}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(20, 20, 25, 25, 'kjv', 'and after vows to make enquiry.', 59, 90, 'theology', 'The Nature of Vows', 'This passage suggests that making enquiries after vows reflects a lack of commitment and sincerity. Many scholars believe that biblical vows represent a significant covenant before God, and treating them lightly can lead to spiritual snares. This emphasizes the importance of integrity in our promises to God and serves as a reminder that our commitments should be taken seriously.', 'person.2.fill', NULL, 'standard', true, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(20, 20, 25, 25, 'kjv', 'It is a snare to the man who devoureth that which is holy,', 0, 58, 'question', 'Understanding Holiness', 'What does it mean to ''devour that which is holy'' in your own life? Consider areas where you may be treating sacred commitments or practices casually. How can this understanding shape your approach to worship and promises made to God?', 'questionmark.circle.fill', NULL, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(20, 20, 25, 25, 'kjv', 'and after vows to make enquiry.', 59, 90, 'greek', 'Key Greek Term', 'ἀνακρίνω (anakrino, G350) - to examine, investigate, or inquire. This term emphasizes the act of scrutinizing one''s commitments and the importance of sincere reflection on vows made to God.', 'textformat.abc', '[{"type": "strongs", "reference": "G350", "description": "Strong''s number for the Greek term"}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(20, 20, 26, 26, 'kjv', 'A wise king scattereth the wicked', 0, 33, 'connection', 'Wisdom in Leadership', 'This phrase connects to Psalm 101:8, where the psalmist declares, ''Morning by morning I will destroy all the wicked in the land.'' Both passages highlight the responsibility of righteous leaders to address wickedness decisively, emphasizing a proactive stance in governance. This connection illustrates the biblical principle that wisdom in leadership is essential for maintaining justice and righteousness in society.', 'link', '[{"type": "crossReference", "reference": "Psalm 101:8", "description": "A parallel emphasis on the role of leaders in addressing wickedness."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini');